{"summary":{"verdict":"BLOCK","one_liner":"Three production-killing issues: fire-and-forget loses events silently, synchronous 2MB XML parsing blocks the event loop under load, and zero error handling means one bad payload crashes the process."},"critical_findings":[{"title":"Fire-and-forget webhook loses events with no recovery path","risk":"Sending 200 OK before processing means if anything after `res.send('OK')` throws (DB down, malformed payload, OOM), the carrier considers the webhook delivered and never retries. At 200 webhooks/min, silent data loss compounds fast.","severity":"Critical","location":"app.post handler, line `res.status(200).send('OK')` at top","reproduction":"1. Send a valid webhook. 2. Kill the DB connection mid-flight. 3. Carrier gets 200 OK. 4. Delivery status never updates. 5. No error logged, no retry, no trace.","fix":"Move the 200 response to AFTER successful processing, inside a try/catch. Return 500 on failure so the carrier retries. If the carrier has a short timeout, queue the work (e.g., Bull/BullMQ) and ack after enqueue — not before processing. Example:

try {
  // ... process ...
  await db.deliveries.updateStatus(...);
  res.status(200).send('OK');
} catch (err) {
  logger.error('Webhook processing failed', { err, trackingNumber: event.trackingNumber });
  res.status(500).send('Processing failed');
}","time_to_fix":"30 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Delivery status must reflect carrier updates reliably"},{"title":"Synchronous XML parsing blocks the Node.js event loop — 200 req/min will starve all connections","risk":"`parseXmlSync` on up to 2MB payloads is CPU-bound and blocks the single event loop thread. At 200 webhooks/min (~3.3/sec), a 50-100ms sync parse per request means the event loop is blocked 15-30% of the time. Spikes cause cascading timeouts for ALL other requests and health checks, potentially triggering restarts.","severity":"Critical","location":"`const parsed = parseXmlSync(xmlData);`","reproduction":"1. Send 10 concurrent webhooks with 2MB XML payloads. 2. Simultaneously call a health-check endpoint. 3. Health check times out because the event loop is blocked parsing XML. 4. Load balancer marks instance unhealthy.","fix":"Replace `parseXmlSync` with an async streaming XML parser (e.g., `fast-xml-parser`'s async API, or `xml2js.parseStringPromise`). For truly large payloads, offload to a worker thread:

const parsed = await parseXmlAsync(xmlData);
// or
const parsed = await runInWorker(() => parseXmlSync(xmlData));","time_to_fix":"30 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"System must remain responsive under peak webhook load"},{"title":"Zero error handling — any unhandled rejection crashes the process or leaks","risk":"After the response is sent, the async work runs detached (fire-and-forget promise). An unhandled exception in `db.deliveries.findByTrackingNumber`, `parseXmlSync`, or `updateStatus` becomes an unhandled promise rejection. In Node 15+ this terminates the process by default. Even with a global handler, there is no per-request error logging, no metrics, and no way to correlate failures to specific tracking numbers.","severity":"Critical","location":"Entire handler body after `res.send('OK')` — no try/catch","reproduction":"1. Send a webhook with `rawXmlPayload: null`. 2. `parseXmlSync(null)` throws. 3. Unhandled promise rejection. 4. Node process crashes (default behavior in Node 15+). 5. All in-flight requests lost.","fix":"Wrap the entire post-response block in try/catch with structured logging. Add input validation before processing:

try {
  if (!event?.trackingNumber || !event?.rawXmlPayload) {
    throw new Error('Invalid webhook payload');
  }
  // ... processing ...
} catch (err) {
  logger.error('Webhook failed', { err, event: event?.trackingNumber });
  // emit metric for alerting
}","time_to_fix":"15 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"System must not crash on malformed input"}],"important_issues":[{"title":"Sequential DB updates in a loop — N+1 write pattern","description":"Each `updateStatus` is awaited sequentially inside a for loop. With many updates per payload, this unnecessarily serializes writes. Use `Promise.all` (with concurrency limit) or a batch UPDATE query.","location":"for (const update of parsed.updates) { await db.deliveries.updateStatus(...) }"},{"title":"DeliveryMap overwrites duplicates silently","description":"All deliveries are fetched by the same `event.trackingNumber`, then keyed by `trackingNumber` in the map. If multiple deliveries share a tracking number (returns, re-ships), only the last one survives in the map. The others are silently dropped.","location":"deliveryMap[delivery.trackingNumber] = delivery;"},{"title":"No request body size limit or validation","description":"The endpoint accepts `rawXmlPayload` up to 2MB with no explicit body size limit configured. An attacker or misbehaving carrier could send arbitrarily large payloads, causing OOM. Add `express.json({ limit: '2mb' })` and validate the payload schema.","location":"const xmlData = event.rawXmlPayload;"}],"suggestions":["Add an idempotency check (e.g., store processed webhook event IDs) to handle carrier retries without double-processing","Add structured logging with correlation IDs (tracking number, webhook event ID) for observability","Consider a queue-based architecture: ack after enqueue to Redis/SQS, process in a worker — decouples ingestion from processing and handles backpressure at 200 req/min","Add request timing metrics to detect event loop blocking before it becomes an outage"],"production_readiness":{"deployment_risks":"All three critical findings are present in the current code. Deploying this under peak load (200 webhooks/min) will result in event loop starvation and silent delivery status loss.","rollback_capability":"No migration or schema change — rollback is a simple redeploy of the previous version.","backward_compatibility":"No breaking changes to external contracts. The carrier sends webhooks; fixing these issues does not change the API surface.","monitoring_coverage":"Zero — no error logging, no metrics, no alerting. Failures are completely invisible.","breaking_changes":{"api_breaking":false,"db_destructive":false,"shared_library":false,"auth_security":false,"data_pipeline":false,"config_changes":false,"details":[]},"safe_to_deploy":false,"rollback_plan":"Redeploy previous container/build artifact. No DB migrations to reverse."},"escalations":[],"confidence":{"level":95,"high_confidence_areas":["Fire-and-forget pattern guarantees silent data loss on any processing error","Synchronous XML parsing will block the event loop — this is a well-documented Node.js anti-pattern","Missing error handling will crash Node 15+ on any unexpected input"],"low_confidence_areas":["Exact event loop blocking duration depends on XML payload sizes and parser implementation speed","Whether the carrier actually retries on non-200 responses (assumed yes, as is standard)"],"assumptions":["Node.js 15+ is in use (unhandled rejections terminate by default)","The carrier webhook contract follows standard retry-on-failure semantics","parseXmlSync is truly synchronous as the name implies"]}}

